…to CPU and GPU

Figure 4. Intel 4004 [4]
The "first commercial available" CPU, the Intel 4004
  • Single-core 4-Bit CPU
  • Transistor count: 2.3k
  • Chip area: 12 mm2
  • 740 kHz
  • Process size: 10000 nm
  • Birthyear: 1971
The FH Technikum Wien "TW8051"
  • Single-core 8-Bit CPU
  • Transistor count: 30k
  • Chip area: 5 mm2
  • 5.3125 MHz
  • Process size: 350 nm
  • Birthyear: 2013
Figure 5. NVIDIA GK110 Kepler GPU [5]
The NVIDIA GK110 Kepler
  • 2880 core 32/64-Bit GPU
  • Transistor count: 7.1 billion
  • Chip area: est. 500-600 mm2
  • 900 MHz
  • Process size: 28 nm
  • Birthyear: 2012

How to get there? - The productivity gap problem

Imagine a designer that can place and route one transistor per minute, therefore he/she would need over 13000 years for the NVIDIA Kepler GK110.

Backend-level reuse and automation
  • Automate chip layout (placement, routing, …)
  • Use standard cells (NOT, AND, OR, Flip-Flops, IOs …)

Now the designer could speed-up by the (estimated) factor of 10.

Only 1300 years for the NVIDIA Kepler GK110!

Frontend-level reuse and automation
  • Use hardware description languages (VHDL, Verilog)
  • Automate design synthesis (translate HDL to logic gates)

This might result in a speed-up by 100 and therefore a total work time (non-stop!) of 1.3 years → 7 years "normal" workload. As a new chip generation is due every 1 to 2 years even this is not enough.

Design reuse and higher level languages
  • Use IP (Intelectual Property) cores, e.g.: CPU, memories, decoders …)
  • SystemC → hardware description with C++
